function maxValue(items, capacity) {
    items.sort((a, b) => (b[0] / b[1]) - (a[0] / a[1]));

    let maxTotalPrice = 0;
    for (const item of items) {
        if (capacity >= item[1]) {
            capacity -= item[1];
            maxTotalPrice += item[0];
        }
        else {
            maxTotalPrice += (item[0] * capacity / item[1]);
            break;
        }
    }

    return maxTotalPrice;
}
```


    The solution starts by sorting the items in descending order based on their price-to-weight ratio. This effectively gives priority to items with a higher "value density". Then, it initializes `maxTotalPrice` to 0, representing the eventual result.

The algorithm iterates through the sorted items, and for each item, it checks if its weight is smaller than the remaining capacity of the bag. If so, it adds the whole item to the bag, and updates the bag capacity accordingly. In case the item's weight is larger than the remaining capacity, the algorithm divides the item into the largest possible part that fits the bag.

For each included item or item part, the algorithm updates the total price.

Once the algorithm has processed all items, it returns the `maxTotalPrice`.

